Comment: This game is a classic example of what happens when black does take to play along openning's strengths. white does a solid job in avoiding exchanges and in the end takes complete control

The modern benoni

The point of blacks thrust is to lure white to d5 and create a pawn imbalance on the opposite board. The disadvantage is that white usually has a slightly better game because of the enduring space advantage in the centre.

As a side note I do not recommend playing ...C5 right away. It is good to keep white guessing with ...e6. This allows you to transpose quickly into king indain lines if you feel things are not right to play the benoni.

Thus far black has followed a very natural-looking development path. However, in this particular position they do not really offer much in the way of counter play. White is able to continue his central build up virtually unmolested, whilst sooner or later black will be left wondering how on earth he ever imagined being able to generate any real counter play. The problem for black is that he suffers from a very cramped position. Thus, he should be aiming toward exchanges.
The bishop clearly belongs on this diagonal, bearing down the d6-pawn and supporting a future e4-e5 advance.
It is always difficult to decide how to defend the d-pawn in such situations, since both e7 and c7 have potential drawbacks for the queen. In principle, I would prefer e7 to c7.
